0.body:
Seven Hills
Rules Sheet
“Rome didn’t burn in a day… right?”

Welcome to Rome! Or rather, what’s left of it? Where there used to be seven beautiful hills there is now a hotbed of monsters, disasters, and deception. As the Gods themselves, surely you and your compatriots are doing everything in their power to save the land you rule. Though some of your colleagues seem a little less helpful than they could be…

Information:
Players: 4-13, ages 12 and up.
Playtime: (to be determined as playtests are averaged out)
Components: 1 Board, 1 Rules Sheet, 7 20-sided Dice, 13 God cards, 13 Loyalty Cards (12 loyal, 1 traitor), 10 unique disaster cards, 9 unique monster cards, 10 unique hero cards.

Objective:
As the loyal gods, you are working with your fellow teammates to either keep the hills surviving until the threat has passed (7 rounds) or vote out the traitor god.

As the traitor god, you are attempting to destroy the hills before 7 rounds are up, all without being caught and voted out.

The hills are considered destroyed when four or more of them have completely run out of health, at which point Rome has fallen.

Setting Up the Board:
Take five disasters from the disaster deck and place them on any five hills, face up.

Take two disasters from the disaster deck and place them on the remaining two hills, face down.


Shuffle the decks of disaster and monster cards together, placing them somewhere everyone can reach them, this is now the draw pile. Set aside a spot where everyone can reach for defeated cards to be placed, this is now the discard pile.
		                          

Place the 20-sided dice on the hills, one per hill, with the 20 facing up. This is the population/health of each of the seven hills.
				

Determine who is going first, any method is viable, though we suggest that the god deck be shuffled face down before every player predicts which god is on top. When predictions are determined, flip the top card, if any prediction is correct, that player goes first. If no prediction was correct, flip the next card, continuing until a predicted card is revealed.

Every player now chooses a god to play as from the god cards, starting with the player going first and continuing clockwise.

Once players have chosen their gods, each player chooses a hero, starting with the player who chose their god last and continuing counterclockwise.

Take one less “loyal” loyalty card than there are players, shuffle these cards face down with the “traitor” loyalty card, and distribute them randomly to players. The players may look at their own loyalty cards, but not anyone else’s.


Finally, every player draws a hand of seven cards from the draw pile.

Beginning Play:
You are now ready to begin playing Seven Hills. Starting with the player who is going first, each player must play a disaster or monster card from their hand to a hill on their turn, they can then optionally use their god power once per game, and optionally play their hero card. This and its following effects constitute a turn. Turns proceed clockwise from the starting player. When every player has had a turn the round is finished.

Anatomy of a turn:
The current player plays any number of monster or disaster cards from their hand onto one hill. This can be any of the hills, but it cannot be changed after the cards are played. These cards are played face-down. The current player then looks at all face-down cards on that hill – the played cards cannot be changed after seeing the cards on the hill.
The current player may optionally use their god power.
The current player may optionally place their hero, face up, on the previously chosen hill.
Cards on hills resolve (see Resolving Cards).
At any point in this process players may discuss the cards they have in hand, have played, their motives, their reasoning, or anything else they feel pertinent to the situation at hand. Any and all lies are allowed. Players may not directly state the numbers on, names of, or elements of any cards for which they know these attributes. Players may discuss these attributes vaguely. Players may lie.
Example: Player A knows that the face-down disaster is a flood, he may say “There’s quite a lot of rain on that hill” or “Things are looking awfully wet over there”. He may not say “That disaster is a flood” or “That hill is flooded right now”.
Damage is dealt to hills. (see Damaging Hills)
Players draw enough cards to return their hand size to seven, play passes clockwise.

Resolving Cards:
(for countered elements, see Elemental Defeats)
Cards may resolve in the following ways:

Beneficial:
Cards resolve beneficially when the played card is either:

A disaster that counters the element of an ongoing disaster, in which case both disasters are defeated and leave play. There is a fire on the hill and a flood is played, the flood puts out the fire.

A disaster that counters the element of a surviving monster, in which case the monster is defeated but the disaster remains in play. A harpy is on the hill and a famine is played, the harpy starves to death.

Played monster(s) are equal in strength to the current monster(s) on the hill, in which case they all take each other down and leave play. Charibdus is terrorizing a hill with a strength of 6, two fawns (3 strength each) are sent down to defeat him – they all kill each other in battle.

A monster (or hero) that does not counter the element of a surviving monster, but has a larger strength stat than the surviving monster, in which case the surviving monster is defeated. Still, the played monster (or hero) remains in play. If a hero card is played face-up and loses strength based on how much damage they took. Hercules (10 strength) is sent down to defeat two Hippocampi (4 strength each) – Hercules successfully defeats them, but his injuries bring him down to 2 strength (10 - 4 - 4).

A monster that counters the element of an ongoing disaster, in which case the disaster is defeated, but the monster remains in play. A drought is ravaging a hill and Scylla is placed – the water brought by Scylla then ends the drought.

Detrimental:
Cards resolve detrimentally when the played card is either:

A disaster that does not counter the ongoing disaster elementally, in which case both disasters remain in play. A drought is on the hill and the player places a plague – the hill is now dealing with both.

A disaster that does not counter the element of a surviving monster, in which case both monster and disaster remain in play. A hill is flooding and a centaur is added to the mix – now the hill has a flood and a wet, angry, centaur.

A monster that does not have a strength stat greater than the surviving monster, in which case both the surviving monster and played monster remain in play. Scylla is tormenting one of the hills and a Strix is played –  the Strix, recognizing it is out of its league, joins Scylla instead.

A monster with a greater strength than a surviving hero, in which case the surviving hero is defeated, as is the played monster A weakened Hercules with a strength of 2 encounters a centaur, the centaur defeats him and takes up residence on its newly won hill.

Players may not lie about whether a card resolves beneficially or detrimentally, but they may lie about why it resolves the way it does.

Example: Player B is the traitor god, and plays a flood disaster on a hill with a monster on it that has a fire element. Player B may not lie about how it resolves, and accurately says “The monster is defeated”. He then places the monster in the defeated pile, revealing what it was in the process. He goes on to lie about why it was defeated, however, stating that he “played a monster that was quite a bit stronger than that one”.

On any beneficial resolution, the current player may choose to flip one face-down card on any hill face-up. They are not required to do so and in some cases, it may be more beneficial not to.

Damaging Hills:
Each hill begins the game with 20 health, represented by the 20-sided die on the hill. Hills are damaged in one of three ways:

Any face-down card on a hill deals one point of damage to that hill.
Any face-up monster on a hill deals half of its strength (rounded down) to that hill.
Any face-up disaster on a hill deals the damage listed on its card to that hill.

When a hill is damaged, subtract that much health from it and turn the die on that hill to the corresponding number. If a hill hits 0 or lower health, the hill has fallen. Remove all cards from the hill and place them in the discard pile. No more cards may be played on this hill.

Elemental Defeats:
In some cases, the nature of the monster* or disaster will cause them to be destroyed by another, these are the cases:

Disaster                                 Weakness(es)
Drought                                 Flood/Tsunami
Earthquake                            Bloodwater
Flood/Tsunami          Earthquake, Volcanic Eruption
Plague                                     Famine
Volcanic Eruption                   Tornado
Bloodwater                             Drought, Wildfires
Famine                                    Flood/Tsunami
Tornado                                 Earthquake, Drought
Wildfires                        Tornado, Flood/Tsunami      
Riots                            Plague, Famine, Earthquake


*The nature of the monster is based on what the monster causes – eg. a Hippocamp, which causes an earthquake, will get rid of a tornado.

Voting out the traitor: 
At the end of rounds 3 and 6, a vote is held. After any desired discussion has ceased, the player who went first will count from three down to zero. Upon saying zero, all players will point at who they wish to vote out of the game. If a majority of players voted for one player, that player is eliminated. They may still speak for the rest of the game, but their turn is skipped. If there is no majority, or there is a tie, no one is voted out. (In the case of 4-player games, a tie results in another round of discussion, then another vote. If there is still a tie, then no one is voted out.) Players may choose not to vote by not pointing at anyone. If the traitor god is voted out, they do not reveal themselves, there is still every chance the monsters and disasters will do their work for them, after all.

If four or more of the hills are destroyed, there is one last emergency vote. There is no discussion before this vote. If the loyal gods successfully vote out the traitor god, the loyal gods win. (in the case of a four-player game, this vote does not occur).

Victory!:
If the loyal gods keep the hills surviving for seven full rounds, or they vote out the traitor god in an emergency vote, they win! Rome survives yet another day, though perhaps with one less god to rule over and protect it.

If the traitor god successfully lies, cheats, and deceives their way into destroying four or more of the seven hills while remaining unsuspected, or seeds enough infighting and chaos that the monsters, disasters, or other gods do that for them, they win! Rome has fallen, and over the ashes they alone reign superior.
